03881nam a22004815i 9780804778879DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222000cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047788797 a10.1515/97808047788792doi  a(DE-B1597)582624  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aP37b.R55 2000eb 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a401/.92211 aRiley, Denise, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Words of Selves :bIdentification, Solidarity, Irony /cDenise Riley. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (240 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAtopia: Philosophy, Political Theory, Aesthetics00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. 'Who, me?' Self-description's linguistic affect -- t2. Linguistic unease -- t3. Lyric selves -- t4. 'The Wounded Fall in the Direction of Their Wound' -- t5. Echo, irony, and the political -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMarlene Dietrich had the last line in Orson Welles's A Touch of Evil: "What does it matter what you say about other people?" The author ponders the question: What does it matter what you say about yourself? She wonders why the requirement to be a something-or-other should be so hard to satisfy in a manner that rings true in the ears of its own subject. She decides that some hesitations and awkwardness in inhabiting many categories of the person—including those celebrated by what is sometimes termed identity politics—need not evidence either psychological weakness or political lack of nerve. Neither an "identity" nor a "nonidentity" can quite convince. But if this discomfort inhering in self-characterization needs to be fully admitted and registered—as something that is simultaneously linguistic and affective—it can also be cheerfully tolerated. Here language is not treated as a guileful thing that leads its speakers astray. Though the business of being called something, and of being positioned by that calling, is often an unhappy affair, irony can offer effective therapy. Even if uncertain and volatile categorizations do trouble the politics that they also shape, they hardly weaken the empathetic solidarity that is distinct from identification. The verbal irony of self-presentation can be politically helpful. Questioning the received diction of the self cannot be dismissed merely as a luxury of those in secure positions, but instead can move toward a conception of a constructive nonidentity. This extended meditation on the language of the self within contemporary social politics also considers the lyrical "I" and linguistic emotionality, the historical status of irony, and the possibilities of a nonidentitarian solidarity that is unapologetically alert to the affect of language.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aPsycholinguistics. 0aSelf-perception. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080477887940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804778879423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804778879/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles